01:33:17,603 --> 01:33:19,729
records, W-2s,

1395
01:33:19,813 --> 01:33:23,816
- with his name on them.
- If you indulge this fantasy, that's your business.

1396
01:33:23,901 --> 01:33:27,862
- Don't make it mine. This meeting is over.
- Sir, if I were to ever get out,

1397
01:33:27,946 --> 01:33:32,950
I would never mention what goes on in here.
I'd be as indictable as you for laundering money.

1398
01:33:34,745 --> 01:33:37,747
Don't ever mention money to me again,
you sorry son of a bitch!

1399
01:33:37,831 --> 01:33:39,707
Not in this office.

1400
01:33:39,708 --> 01:33:41,834
Not anywhere! Get in here now.

1401
01:33:41,919 --> 01:33:45,171
I'm just trying to set your mind at ease,
that's all. Sir, I...

1402
01:33:45,255 --> 01:33:46,631
Solitary. A month.

1403
01:33:46,715 --> 01:33:48,883
- Yes, sir.
- What's the matter with you?

1404
01:33:48,967 --> 01:33:52,220
- Get him out of here.
- This is my chance to get out! Don't you see that?

1405
01:33:52,221 --> 01:33:54,222
It's my life! Don't you understand?

1406
01:33:54,306 --> 01:33:56,766
- Get him out! Get him out!
- This is my life!

1407
01:33:56,850 --> 01:33:58,101
No!

1408
01:33:58,185 --> 01:34:00,019
A month in the hole.

1409
01:34:00,104 --> 01:34:02,689
It's the longest damn stretch I ever heard of.

1410
01:34:02,773 --> 01:34:04,565
It's all my fault.

1411
01:34:04,650 --> 01:34:06,067
Oh, bullshit.

1412
01:34:06,151 --> 01:34:09,445
You didn't pull the trigger
and you certainly didn't convict him.

1413
01:34:09,530 --> 01:34:11,906
Red, are you saying that Andy is innocent?

1414
01:34:11,990 --> 01:34:14,158
I mean, for real innocent?

1415
01:34:14,243 --> 01:34:16,285
It looks that way.

1416
01:34:16,370 --> 01:34:18,413
Sweet Jesus.

1417
01:34:18,497 --> 01:34:20,540
How long's he been here now?

1418
01:34:20,624 --> 01:34:22,667
1947. What is that?

1419
01:34:22,751 --> 01:34:24,293
- 19 years.
<font color="#808080">TOMMY :</font> 19 years...

1420
01:34:24,378 --> 01:34:27,004
<i><font color="#808080">GUARD :</font> Williams, Thomas.</i>
- Yeah, over here.

1421
01:34:29,383 --> 01:34:31,634
- Paxon, Edward.
- Yeah.

1422
01:34:32,845 --> 01:34:35,763
What you got?
Board of Education.

1423
01:34:35,848 --> 01:34:38,516
- The son of a bitch mailed it.
- Looks like he did.

1424
01:34:38,600 --> 01:34:41,644
Are you gonna open it or stand there
with your thumb up your butt?

1425
01:34:41,729 --> 01:34:43,813
The thumb up my butt sounds better.

1426
01:34:44,857 --> 01:34:47,608
Hey, Skeet, come on,
give me that, you shithead.

1427
01:34:48,652 --> 01:34:50,862
- Floyd, come on.
- Over here, over here!

1428
01:34:51,905 --> 01:34:53,990
Hey, Red!

1429
01:34:55,117 --> 01:34:57,535
Come on, will you throw that away, please?

1430
01:35:03,125 --> 01:35:05,209
Well, shit.

1431
01:35:17,431 --> 01:35:20,141
The kid passed. C+ average.

1432
01:35:20,225 --> 01:35:22,310
Thought you'd like to know.

1433
01:35:38,869 --> 01:35:40,953
The Warden wants to talk.

1434
01:35:54,343 --> 01:35:55,468
Out here?

1435
01:35:55,552 --> 01:35:57,637
That's what the man said.

1436
01:36:13,946 --> 01:36:15,738
Warden?

1437
01:36:15,823 --> 01:36:17,907
Tommy.

1438
01:36:23,372 --> 01:36:24,831
Tommy...

1439
01:36:24,915 --> 01:36:29,001
I'm asking you to keep this conversation
just between us.

1440
01:36:30,420 --> 01:36:32,505
I feel awkward enough as it is.

1441
01:36:50,983 --> 01:36:53,067
We got a situation here.

1442
01:36:54,111 --> 01:36:56,153
I think you can appreciate that.

1443
01:36:56,238 --> 01:36:57,697
Yes, sir.

1444
01:36:57,781 --> 01:36:59,282
I sure can.

1445
01:36:59,366 --> 01:37:03,411
I tell you, son, this thing really came along
and knocked my wind out.

1446
01:37:05,122 --> 01:37:07,665
It's got me up nights, that's the truth.

1447
01:37:09,877 --> 01:37:11,961
The right thing to do.

1448
01:37:13,297 --> 01:37:16,299
Sometimes it's hard to know what that is.

1449
01:37:18,010 --> 01:37:20,052
You understand?

1450
01:37:21,430 --> 01:37:23,514
I need your help, son.

1451
01:37:24,933 --> 01:37:27,018
If I'm going to move on this,

1452
01:37:27,019 --> 01:37:29,770
there can't be the least little shred of doubt.

1453
01:37:31,315 --> 01:37:34,734
I have to know
if what you told Dufresne was the truth.

1454
01:37:34,818 --> 01:37:36,402
Yes, sir.

1455
01:37:36,403 --> 01:37:38,029
Absolutely.

1456
01:37:38,113 --> 01:37:41,198
Would you be willing
to swear before a judge and jury,

1457
01:37:41,283 --> 01:37:43,701
having placed your hand on the Good Book

1458
01:37:43,702 --> 01:37:46,412
and taken an oath before Almighty God himself?

1459
01:37:46,496 --> 01:37:48,623
Just give me that chance.

1460
01:37:52,544 --> 01:37:54,211
That's what I thought.

1461
01:38:26,662 --> 01:38:28,746
<font color="#ff00ff">(Keys rattle)</font>

1462
01:38:41,301 --> 01:38:43,386
I'm sure by now you've heard...

1463
01:38:44,638 --> 01:38:46,013
A terrible thing.

1464
01:38:47,474 --> 01:38:51,060
A man that young, less than a year to go,
trying to escape.

1465
01:38:52,145 --> 01:38:54,772
It broke Captain Hadley's heart to shoot him.

1466
01:38:55,816 --> 01:38:57,900
Truly, it did.

1467
01:38:59,945 --> 01:39:02,029
We just have to put it behind us.

1468
01:39:04,199 --> 01:39:05,616
Move on.

1469
01:39:07,077 --> 01:39:08,953
I'm done.

1470
01:39:09,997 --> 01:39:12,081
Everything stops.

1471
01:39:13,125 --> 01:39:15,960
Get someone else to run your scams.

1472
01:39:17,295 --> 01:39:19,380
Nothing stops.

1473
01:39:20,424 --> 01:39:22,508
Nothing.

1474
01:39:24,261 --> 01:39:26,345
Or you will do the hardest time there is.

1475
01:39:28,223 --> 01:39:30,808
No more protection from the guards.

1476
01:39:30,892 --> 01:39:33,227
I'll pull you out of that one-bunk Hilton

1477
01:39:33,311 --> 01:39:35,479
and cast you down with the Sodomites.

1478
01:39:37,232 --> 01:39:39,734
You'll think you've been fucked by a train.

1479
01:39:41,028 --> 01:39:43,070
And the library?

1480
01:39:43,155 --> 01:39:44,280
Gone.

1481
01:39:44,364 --> 01:39:46,741
Sealed off, brick by brick.

1482
01:39:47,784 --> 01:39:50,578
We'll have us a little book barbecue in the yard.

1483
01:39:50,662 --> 01:39:52,705
They'll see the flames for miles.

1484
01:39:52,789 --> 01:39:55,291
We'll dance around it like wild Injuns.

1485
01:39:56,877 --> 01:39:58,794
You understand me?

1486
01:39:58,879 --> 01:40:00,963
Catching my drift?

1487
01:40:04,051 --> 01:40:06,135
Or am I being obtuse?

1488
01:40:17,272 --> 01:40:19,398
Give him another month to think about it.

1489
01:40:27,908 --> 01:40:29,992
<font color="#ff00ff">(Lock clicks)</font>

1490
01:41:06,988 --> 01:41:10,032
My wife used to say I'm a hard man to know.

1491
01:41:10,117 --> 01:41:12,201
Like a closed book.

1492
01:41:13,411 --> 01:41:16,163
Complained about it all the time.

1493
01:41:16,248 --> 01:41:18,332
She was beautiful.

1494
01:41:20,544 --> 01:41:22,628
God, I loved her.

1495
01:41:25,632 --> 01:41:27,967
I just didn't know how to show it, that's all.

1496
01:41:30,470 --> 01:41:32,555
I killed her, Red.

1497
01:41:34,015 --> 01:41:36,100
I didn't pull the trigger.

1498
01:41:37,519 --> 01:41:39,603
But I drove her away.

1499
01:41:40,814 --> 01:41:43,357
That's why she died, because of me.

1500
01:41:43,441 --> 01:41:45,526
The way I am.

1501
01:41:53,869 --> 01:41:55,953
That don't make you a murderer.

1502
01:41:59,166 --> 01:42:01,250
A bad husband, maybe.

1503
01:42:04,629 --> 01:42:08,007
Feel bad about it if you want to,
but you didn't pull the trigger.

1504
01:42:08,091 --> 01:42:09,508
No, I didn't.

1505
01:42:09,593 --> 01:42:11,635
Somebody else did.

1506
01:42:12,929 --> 01:42:15,014
And I wound up in here.

1507
01:42:17,392 --> 01:42:19,476
Bad luck, I guess.

1508
01:42:22,397 --> 01:42:24,106
Yeah.

1509
01:42:24,191 --> 01:42:26,483
It floats around.

1510
01:42:26,568 --> 01:42:29,028
It's got to land on somebody.

1511
01:42:29,112 --> 01:42:31,363
It was my turn, that's all.

1512
01:42:32,449 --> 01:42:34,909
I was in the path of the tornado.

1513
01:42:41,499 --> 01:42:45,252
I just didn't expect
the storm would last as long as it has.

1514
01:42:49,341 --> 01:42:51,258
Do you think you'll ever get out of here?

1515
01:42:52,510 --> 01:42:54,178
Me?

1516
01:42:56,473 --> 01:42:57,932
Yeah.

1517
01:42:58,975 --> 01:43:00,935
One day, when I've got a long, white beard

1518
01:43:01,019 --> 01:43:04,521
and two or three marbles rolling around upstairs,
they'll let me out.

1519
01:43:04,941 --> 01:43:07,025
I tell you where I'd go.

1520
01:43:08,236 --> 01:43:09,862
Zihuatanejo.

1521
01:43:09,946 --> 01:43:11,864
Zi...what?

1522
01:43:11,948 --> 01:43:13,991
Zihuatanejo.

1523
01:43:14,075 --> 01:43:16,160
It's in Mexico.

1524
01:43:17,954 --> 01:43:20,164
A little place on the Pacific Ocean.

1525
01:43:21,416 --> 01:43:23,792
You know what the Mexicans say
about the Pacific?

1526
01:43:23,877 --> 01:43:25,335
No.

1527
01:43:25,420 --> 01:43:27,504
They say it has no memory.

1528
01:43:29,966 --> 01:43:32,509
That's where I want to live the rest of my life.

1529
01:43:34,095 --> 01:43:36,180
A warm place with no memory.

1530
01:43:39,476 --> 01:43:41,769
Open up a little hotel,

1531
01:43:43,605 --> 01:43:45,481
right on the beach.

1532
01:43:45,565 --> 01:43:47,608
Buy some worthless old boat,

1533
01:43:47,692 --> 01:43:49,777
fix it up new.

1534
01:43:52,739 --> 01:43:53,947
Take my guests out.

1535
01:43:54,032 --> 01:43:56,116
Charter fishing.

1536
01:44:00,038 --> 01:44:02,664
Zihuatanejo, huh?

1537
01:44:05,293 --> 01:44:09,171
In a place like that, I could use a man
who knows how to get things.

1538
01:44:15,595 --> 01:44:18,305
I don't think I could make it on the outside, Andy.

1539
01:44:25,063 --> 01:44:27,147
I've been in here most of my life.

1540
01:44:28,650 --> 01:44:30,442
I'm an institutional man now.

1541
01:44:30,527 --> 01:44:32,611
Just like Brooks was.

1542
01:44:34,030 --> 01:44:36,281
Well, you underestimate yourself.

1543
01:44:36,366 --> 01:44:38,450
I don't think so.

1544
01:44:41,079 --> 01:44:45,290
I mean...in here, I'm the guy
who can get things for you, sure.

1545
01:44:45,375 --> 01:44:49,294
But outside, all you need is the Yellow Pages.

1546
01:44:49,379 --> 01:44:51,797
Hell, I wouldn't even know where to begin.

1547
01:44:53,883 --> 01:44:56,218
The Pacific Ocean?

1548
01:44:56,302 --> 01:44:58,345
Shit.

1549
01:44:58,429 --> 01:45:01,598
- About scare me to death, something that big.
- Not me.

1550
01:45:01,683 --> 01:45:05,143
I didn't shoot my wife and I didn't shoot her lover.

1551
01:45:07,063 --> 01:45:10,691
Whatever mistakes I've made,
I've paid for them and then some.

1552
01:45:10,775 --> 01:45:12,943
That hotel, that boat.

1553
01:45:14,529 --> 01:45:16,697
I don't think that's too much to ask.

1554
01:45:21,327 --> 01:45:24,204
I don't think you ought to be
doing this to yourself, Andy.

1555
01:45:24,289 --> 01:45:26,331
These are just shitty pipe dreams.

1556
01:45:26,416 --> 01:45:29,376
I mean, Mexico is way the hell down there
and you're in here.

1557
01:45:29,460 --> 01:45:31,503
And that's the way it is.

1558
01:45:31,588 --> 01:45:34,214
Yeah, right. That's the way it is.

1559
01:45:35,967 --> 01:45:38,051
It's down there and I'm in here.

1560
01:45:40,763 --> 01:45:43,557
I guess it comes down to a simple choice, really.

1561
01:45:46,394 --> 01:45:48,437
Get busy living

1562
01:45:48,521 --> 01:45:51,440
or get busy dying.

1563
01:45:55,236 --> 01:45:57,321
Andy.

1564
01:45:59,782 --> 01:46:01,867
Red.

1565
01:46:02,911 --> 01:46:05,329
If you ever get out of here, do me a favor.

1566
01:46:05,413 --> 01:46:07,247
Sure, Andy.

1567
01:46:07,332 --> 01:46:08,665
Anything.

1568
01:46:09,751 --> 01:46:13,211
There's a big hayfield up near Buxton.
You know where Buxton is?

1569
01:46:15,214 --> 01:46:19,009
- Well, just... There's a lot of hayfields up there.
- One in particular.

1570
01:46:19,093 --> 01:46:21,136
It's got a long rock wall

1571
01:46:21,220 --> 01:46:23,138
with a big oak tree at the north end.

1572
01:46:23,222 --> 01:46:25,933
It's like something out of a Robert Frost poem.

1573
01:46:27,310 --> 01:46:30,020
It's where I asked my wife to marry me.

1574
01:46:31,230 --> 01:46:35,025
We went there for a picnic
and made love under that oak.

1575
01:46:36,527 --> 01:46:38,612
I asked and she said yes.

1576
01:46:42,742 --> 01:46:44,785
Promise me, Red,

1577
01:46:44,869 --> 01:46:46,870
if you ever get out,

1578
01:46:46,955 --> 01:46:48,997
find that spot.

1579
01:46:50,041 --> 01:46:55,504
At the base of that wall, you'll find a rock that has
no earthly business in a Maine hayfield.

1580
01:46:55,588 --> 01:46:58,090
A piece of black, volcanic glass.

1581
01:47:01,260 --> 01:47:04,054
There's something buried under it
I want you to have.

1582
01:47:04,138 --> 01:47:06,139
What, Andy?

1583
01:47:06,224 --> 01:47:08,308
What's buried under there?

1584
01:47:10,103 --> 01:47:13,480
You'll have to pry it up to see.

1585
01:47:18,820 --> 01:47:20,904
No, I'm telling you, the guy is...

1586
01:47:21,948 --> 01:47:24,032
He's talking funnier.

1587
01:47:24,117 --> 01:47:27,494
- I'm really worried about him.
- We ought to keep an eye on him.

1588
01:47:27,578 --> 01:47:31,623
That's fine during the day,
but at night he's got that cell all to himself.

1589
01:47:32,709 --> 01:47:34,167
Oh, Lord.

1590
01:47:34,252 --> 01:47:36,294
What?

1591
01:47:37,964 --> 01:47:40,298
Andy come down to the loading dock today.

1592
01:47:40,383 --> 01:47:43,885
- He asked me for a length of rope.
- Rope?

1593
01:47:43,970 --> 01:47:45,804
Six feet long.

1594
01:47:45,888 --> 01:47:47,347
And you gave it to him?

1595
01:47:47,432 --> 01:47:50,100
Sure I did. Why wouldn't I?

1596
01:47:50,101 --> 01:47:51,810
Jesus, Heywood.

1597
01:47:51,894 --> 01:47:54,146
Hey, how the hell was I supposed to know?

1598
01:47:54,230 --> 01:47:56,148
Remember Brooks Hatlen?

1599
01:47:56,232 --> 01:47:57,274
No.

1600
01:47:58,317 --> 01:48:00,527
Andy would never do that.

1601
01:48:00,528 --> 01:48:02,612
Never.

1602
01:48:03,656 --> 01:48:05,741
I don't know.

1603
01:48:07,785 --> 01:48:09,870
Every man has his breaking point.

1604
01:48:12,498 --> 01:48:13,749
Lickety-split.

1605
01:48:13,833 --> 01:48:16,710
- I want to get home.
- Just about finished, sir.

1606
01:48:32,810 --> 01:48:34,895
Three deposits tonight.

1607
01:48:43,279 --> 01:48:45,363
Get my stuff down to the laundry.

1608
01:48:45,364 --> 01:48:48,825
And shine my shoes.
I want 'em looking like mirrors.

1609
01:48:48,910 --> 01:48:50,285
Yes, sir.

1610
01:48:55,583 --> 01:48:57,250
It's good having you back, Andy.

1611
01:48:57,335 --> 01:49:00,087
The place wasn't the same without you.

1612
01:49:02,215 --> 01:49:04,299
<font color="#ff00ff">(Whistles)</font>

1613
01:49:47,135 --> 01:49:49,886
<i><font color="#808080">GUARD :</font> Lights out!</i>
<font color="#ff00ff">(Click of light switches)</font>

1614
01:49:54,183 --> 01:49:56,268
<font color="#ff00ff">(Footsteps)</font>

1615
01:50:02,150 --> 01:50:04,234
<font color="#ff00ff">(Outer door closes)</font>

1616
01:50:20,626 --> 01:50:22,919
<i><font color="#808080">RED :</font> I've had some long nights in stir.</i>

1617
01:50:23,963 --> 01:50:26,673
<i>Alone in the dark with nothing but your thoughts,</i>

1618
01:50:26,757 --> 01:50:28,592
<i>time can draw out like a blade.</i>

1619
01:50:28,593 --> 01:50:30,677
<font color="#ff00ff">(Thunder rumbles)</font>

1620
01:50:34,974 --> 01:50:37,309
<i>That was the longest night of my life.</i>

1621
01:50:47,528 --> 01:50:49,863
<font color="#ff00ff">(Gate buzzer)</font>

1622
01:50:53,451 --> 01:50:55,076
<i><font color="#808080">GUARD :</font> Give me a count.</i>

1623
01:50:59,415 --> 01:51:01,458
<i>Tier 3 South. Clear.</i>

1624
01:51:01,542 --> 01:51:02,876
<i>Tier 4 North. Clear.</i>

1625
01:51:02,960 --> 01:51:06,546
<i>- Tier 3 North. Clear.</i>
- Man missing on Tier 2.

1626
01:51:06,631 --> 01:51:09,716
- Cell 245.
- Dufresne.

1627
01:51:09,800 --> 01:51:12,719
Get your ass out here, boy.
You're holding up the show.

1628
01:51:15,223 --> 01:51:19,267
Don't make me come down there.
I'll thump your skull for you.

1629
01:51:26,859 --> 01:51:30,237
Damn it, Dufresne, you're putting me behind!
I got a schedule to keep.

1630
01:51:30,321 --> 01:51:33,406
You'd better be sick or dead in there,
I shit you not!

1631
01:51:33,491 --> 01:51:35,325
You hear me?

1632
01:51:41,832 --> 01:51:43,917
Oh, my holy God.

1633
01:51:56,013 --> 01:51:58,098
<font color="#ff00ff">(Siren wails)</font>

1634
01:52:00,768 --> 01:52:03,478
I want every man on this cell block questioned.

1635
01:52:03,479 --> 01:52:05,689
- Start with that friend of his.
- Who?

1636
01:52:05,773 --> 01:52:06,982
Him!

1637
01:52:08,901 --> 01:52:10,986
Open 237.

1638
01:52:13,990 --> 01:52:16,116
What do you mean, he just wasn't here?

1639
01:52:16,200 --> 01:52:17,742
Don't say that to me, Haig.

1640
01:52:17,827 --> 01:52:20,078
Don't say that to me again.

1641
01:52:20,162 --> 01:52:21,246
But, sir, he wasn't.

1642
01:52:21,330 --> 01:52:23,498
I can see that, Haig!

1643
01:52:23,582 --> 01:52:25,375
You think I'm blind?

1644
01:52:25,376 --> 01:52:28,503
Is that what you're saying? Am I blind, Haig?

1645
01:52:28,587 --> 01:52:29,587
No, sir.

1646
01:52:29,672 --> 01:52:31,715
What about you?

1647
01:52:31,799 --> 01:52:33,633
Are you blind?

1648
01:52:33,718 --> 01:52:36,261
- Tell me what this is.
- Last night's count.

1649
01:52:36,345 --> 01:52:39,639
You see Dufresne's name there?
I sure do. See? Right there.

1650
01:52:39,724 --> 01:52:41,599
Dufresne.

1651
01:52:42,852 --> 01:52:44,519
He was in his cell at lights out.

1652
01:52:44,603 --> 01:52:47,814
It stands to reason
he'd still be here in the morning.

1653
01:52:48,899 --> 01:52:50,775
I want him found.

1654
01:52:50,860 --> 01:52:53,445
Not tomorrow, not after breakfast.

1655
01:52:53,529 --> 01:52:54,571
Now!

1656
01:52:54,572 --> 01:52:56,072
Yes, sir!

1657
01:52:57,199 --> 01:52:59,784
Let's go, let's go!
Move your butts! Move it!

1658
01:53:02,621 --> 01:53:03,663
Stand.

1659
01:53:04,790 --> 01:53:06,041
Well?

1660
01:53:09,420 --> 01:53:10,545
Well, what?

1661
01:53:10,629 --> 01:53:14,090
I see you two all the time.
You're thick as thieves, you are.

1662
01:53:15,134 --> 01:53:16,760
He must have said something.

1663
01:53:16,844 --> 01:53:18,887
No, sir, Warden.

1664
01:53:18,971 --> 01:53:20,430
Not a word.

1665
01:53:22,433 --> 01:53:24,434
Lord, it's a miracle!

1666
01:53:25,478 --> 01:53:27,937
A man up and vanished like a fart in the wind.

1667
01:53:28,022 --> 01:53:29,773
Nothing left but...

1668
01:53:29,857 --> 01:53:32,776
some damn rocks on a windowsill.

1669
01:53:32,860 --> 01:53:34,611
And that cupcake on the wall.

1670
01:53:34,695 --> 01:53:36,321
Let's ask her.

1671
01:53:36,405 --> 01:53:40,367
Maybe she knows. What say there,
Fuzzy Britches? Feel like talking?

1672
01:53:41,452 --> 01:53:42,535
Ah...

1673
01:53:42,536 --> 01:53:43,995
I guess not.

1674
01:53:44,080 --> 01:53:46,956
Why should she be any different?

1675
01:53:47,041 --> 01:53:49,501
This is a conspiracy.

1676
01:53:49,585 --> 01:53:51,795
That's what this is.

1677
01:53:51,879 --> 01:53:53,421
One big...

1678
01:53:53,506 --> 01:53:56,257
damn conspiracy!

1679
01:53:56,342 --> 01:53:59,010
And everyone's in on it!

1680
01:53:59,095 --> 01:54:00,387
Including her!

1681
01:54:01,722 --> 01:54:03,390
<font color="#ff00ff">(Clattering)</font>

1682
01:54:27,164 --> 01:54:28,873
<font color="#ff00ff">(Sirens blare)</font>

1683
01:54:35,047 --> 01:54:36,923
<i><font color="#808080">RED :</font> In 1966,</i>

1684
01:54:37,007 --> 01:54:39,676
<i>Andy Dufresne escaped</i>

1685
01:54:39,760 --> 01:54:41,845
<i>from Shawshank Prison.</i>

1686
01:54:43,514 --> 01:54:46,266
<i>All they found of him
was a muddy set of prison clothes,</i>

1687
01:54:46,350 --> 01:54:48,393
<i>a bar of soap</i>

1688
01:54:48,477 --> 01:54:52,856
<i>and an old rock hammer
damn near worn down to the nub.</i>

1689
01:54:57,236 --> 01:55:02,073
<i>I remember thinking it would take a man
600 years to tunnel through the wall with it.</i>

1690
01:55:02,158 --> 01:55:04,868
<i>Old Andy did it in less than 20.</i>

1691
01:55:23,429 --> 01:55:25,513
<i>Oh, Andy loved geology.</i>

1692
01:55:26,557 --> 01:55:30,059
<i>I imagine it appealed to his meticulous nature.</i>

1693
01:55:30,144 --> 01:55:32,437
<i>An Ice Age here,</i>

1694
01:55:32,521 --> 01:55:35,106
<i>a million years of mountain-building there.</i>

1695
01:55:36,150 --> 01:55:38,568
<i>Geology is the study of pressure and time.</i>

1696
01:55:39,778 --> 01:55:41,821
<i>That's all it takes, really.</i>

1697
01:55:41,906 --> 01:55:43,948
<i>Pressure...</i>

1698
01:55:44,033 --> 01:55:45,909
<i>and time.</i>

1699
01:55:45,993 --> 01:55:49,329
<i>That and a big goddamn poster.</i>

1700
01:55:50,414 --> 01:55:52,457
<font color="#ff00ff">(Coughing)</font>

1701
01:55:52,541 --> 01:55:53,917
<i>Like I said,</i>

1702
01:55:53,918 --> 01:55:57,712
<i>in prison, a man will do most anything
to keep his mind occupied.</i>

1703
01:56:00,508 --> 01:56:05,678
<i>It turns out Andy's favorite hobby
was toting his wall out into the exercise yard.</i>

1704
01:56:05,763 --> 01:56:07,847
<i>A handful at a time.</i>

1705
01:56:09,683 --> 01:56:11,851
I guess after Tommy was killed,

1706
01:56:11,936 --> 01:56:14,771
Andy decided he'd been here
just about long enough.

1707
01:56:14,855 --> 01:56:17,065
Lickety-split. I want to get home.

1708
01:56:18,359 --> 01:56:20,443
I'm just about finished, sir.

1709
01:56:41,840 --> 01:56:43,925
Three deposits tonight.

1710
01:56:51,100 --> 01:56:53,142
<i><font color="#808080">RED :</font> Andy did like he was told.</i>

1711
01:56:54,186 --> 01:56:57,689
<i>Buffed those shoes to a high mirror shine.</i>

1712
01:57:01,277 --> 01:57:03,319
<i>The guard simply didn't notice.</i>

1713
01:57:03,404 --> 01:57:05,446
<i>Neither did I.</i>

1714
01:57:05,531 --> 01:57:09,867
<i>I mean, seriously, how often
do you really look at a man's shoes?</i>

1715
01:57:44,570 --> 01:57:46,654
<font color="#ff00ff">(Thunderclap)</font>

1716
01:59:13,909 --> 01:59:20,081
<i>Andy crawled to freedom through 500 yards
of shit-smelling foulness I can't even imagine.</i>

1717
01:59:20,165 --> 01:59:21,332
<font color="#ff00ff">(Gags)</font>

1718
01:59:21,417 --> 01:59:23,418
<i>Or maybe I just don't want to.</i>

1719
01:59:23,502 --> 01:59:25,586
<font color="#ff00ff">(Coughs and spits)</font>

1720
01:59:28,132 --> 01:59:30,341
<i>500 yards.</i>

1721
01:59:31,385 --> 01:59:33,886
<i>That's the length of five football fields.</i>

1722
01:59:34,930 --> 01:59:37,181
<i>Just shy of half a mile.</i>

1723
02:00:18,724 --> 02:00:20,433
<font color="#ff00ff">(Laughs)</font>

1724
02:00:32,404 --> 02:00:36,949
<i><font color="#808080">RED :</font> The next morning, right about the time
Raquel was spilling her little secret,</i>

1725
02:00:37,034 --> 02:00:40,453
<i>a man nobody ever laid eyes on before</i>

1726
02:00:40,537 --> 02:00:42,955
<i>strode into the Maine National Bank.</i>

1727
02:00:43,040 --> 02:00:45,082
<i>Until that moment,</i>

1728
02:00:45,167 --> 02:00:47,043
<i>he didn't exist,</i>

1729
02:00:47,127 --> 02:00:48,461
<i>except on paper.</i>

1730
02:00:48,545 --> 02:00:49,587
<i><font color="#808080">WOMEN :</font> May I help you?</i>

1731
02:00:49,671 --> 02:00:51,714
<i><font color="#808080">RED :</font> He had all the proper ID,</i>

1732
02:00:51,799 --> 02:00:55,426
<i>driver's license, birth certificate,
social security card.</i>

1733
02:00:55,511 --> 02:00:58,805
<i>And the signature was a spot-on match.</i>

1734
02:00:58,889 --> 02:01:01,933
I must say, I'm sorry to be losing your business.

1735
02:01:02,017 --> 02:01:04,018
I hope you'll enjoy living abroad.

1736
02:01:04,102 --> 02:01:05,895
Thank you.

1737
02:01:05,979 --> 02:01:07,772
I'm sure I will.

1738
02:01:07,856 --> 02:01:09,982
Here's your cashier's check, sir.

1739
02:01:10,067 --> 02:01:12,109
Will there be anything else?

1740
02:01:12,194 --> 02:01:13,194
Please...

1741
02:01:13,278 --> 02:01:16,364
Would you add this to your outgoing mail?

1742
02:01:16,448 --> 02:01:18,658
I'd be happy to.

1743
02:01:18,742 --> 02:01:21,077
- Good day, sir.
- Good day.

1744
02:01:21,161 --> 02:01:25,957
<i><font color="#808080">RED :</font> Mr. Stevens visited nearly a dozen banks
in the Portland area that morning.</i>

1745
02:01:27,125 --> 02:01:33,589
<i>All told, he blew town with better than $370,000
of Warden Norton's money.</i>

1746
02:01:33,674 --> 02:01:36,133
<i>Severance pay for 19 years.</i>

1747
02:01:36,218 --> 02:01:38,302
<font color="#ff00ff">(Phone rings)</font>

1748
02:01:44,268 --> 02:01:46,561
<i><font color="#808080">WOMEN : </font>Good morning, Portland Daily Bugle.</i>

1749
02:01:54,236 --> 02:01:56,320
<font color="#ff00ff">(Sirens wail)</font>

1750
02:02:25,517 --> 02:02:27,560
<font color="#ff00ff">(Sirens approaching)</font>

1751
02:02:39,281 --> 02:02:42,283
Byron Hadley?
You have the right to remain silent.

1752
02:02:42,367 --> 02:02:46,996
If you give up the right to remain silent, anything
you say will be held against you in court.

1753
02:02:47,080 --> 02:02:48,956
<i><font color="#808080">RED :</font> I wasn't there to see it.</i>

1754
02:02:49,041 --> 02:02:53,920
<i>But I hear Byron Hadley started sobbing
like a little girl when they took him away.</i>

1755
02:02:59,343 --> 02:03:02,136
<i>Norton had no intention of going that quietly.</i>

1756
02:03:18,111 --> 02:03:19,570
<i>Samuel Norton?</i>

1757
02:03:19,655 --> 02:03:22,907
<i>We have a warrant for your arrest. Open up.</i>
<font color="#ff00ff">(Banging on door)</font>

1758
02:03:25,786 --> 02:03:26,911
Norton!

1759
02:03:26,995 --> 02:03:28,663
Open the door.

1760
02:03:28,747 --> 02:03:30,498
<i>I'm not sure which key it is.</i>

1761
02:03:33,377 --> 02:03:35,044
<i>Norton!</i>

1762
02:03:40,509 --> 02:03:42,593
<i>Make it easy on yourself, Norton.</i>

1763
02:03:53,897 --> 02:03:57,483
<i><font color="#808080">RED :</font> I like to think
the last thing that went through his head,</i>

1764
02:03:57,567 --> 02:03:59,276
<i>other than that bullet,</i>

1765
02:03:59,361 --> 02:04:03,364
<i>was to wonder how the hell
Andy Dufresne ever got the best of him.</i>

1766
02:04:05,033 --> 02:04:06,117
Carter, James...

1767
02:04:06,201 --> 02:04:09,578
<i><font color="#808080">RED :</font> Not long after the Warden
deprived us of his company,</i>

1768
02:04:09,663 --> 02:04:11,914
<i>I got a postcard in the mail.</i>

1769
02:04:13,625 --> 02:04:16,043
<i>It was blank but the postmark said...</i>

1770
02:04:16,128 --> 02:04:18,879
<i>Fort Hancock, Texas.</i>

1771
02:04:18,964 --> 02:04:21,007
<i>Fort Hancock.</i>

1772
02:04:21,091 --> 02:04:23,134
<i>Right on the border.</i>

1773
02:04:23,218 --> 02:04:25,261
<i>That's where Andy crossed.</i>

1774
02:04:25,345 --> 02:04:29,223
<i>When I picture him heading south
in his own car with the top down,</i>

1775
02:04:30,267 --> 02:04:32,351
<i>it always makes me laugh.</i>
<font color="#ff00ff">(Chuckle)</font>

1776
02:04:33,770 --> 02:04:35,813
<i>Andy Dufresne,</i>

1777
02:04:35,897 --> 02:04:38,274
<i>who crawled through a river of shit</i>

1778
02:04:38,358 --> 02:04:40,443
<i>and came out clean on the other side.</i>

1779
02:04:41,653 --> 02:04:43,696
<i>Andy Dufresne,</i>

1780
02:04:43,780 --> 02:04:45,698
<i>headed for the Pacific.</i>

1781
02:04:48,285 --> 02:04:50,327
Hadley's got him by the toes, right?

1782
02:04:50,412 --> 02:04:54,623
And he says, "I believe this boy's
about to have himself an accident."

1783
02:04:54,708 --> 02:04:57,877
<i><font color="#808080">RED :</font> Those of us who knew him best
talk about him often.</i>

1784
02:04:57,961 --> 02:05:00,212
<i>I swear, the stuff he pulled...</i>

1785
02:05:00,297 --> 02:05:02,798
"These friends of mine
could use a couple of beers!"

1786
02:05:02,883 --> 02:05:04,967
- And he got it.
- And he got it!

1787
02:05:06,136 --> 02:05:08,512
<i><font color="#808080">RED :</font> Sometimes it makes me sad, though,</i>

1788
02:05:08,597 --> 02:05:10,639
<i>Andy being gone.</i>

1789
02:05:10,724 --> 02:05:14,727
<i>I have to remind myself
that some birds aren't meant to be caged.</i>

1790
02:05:15,812 --> 02:05:17,897
<i>Their feathers are just too bright.</i>

1791
02:05:19,441 --> 02:05:21,484
<i>And when they fly away,</i>

1792
02:05:21,568 --> 02:05:25,488
<i>the part of you that knows
it was a sin to lock them up does rejoice.</i>

1793
02:05:27,240 --> 02:05:28,699
<i>But still...</i>

1794
02:05:28,784 --> 02:05:32,953
<i>the place you live in is that much more drab
and empty that they're gone.</i>

1795
02:05:37,501 --> 02:05:39,752
<i>I guess I just miss my friend.</i>

1796
02:06:03,735 --> 02:06:05,611
Please sit down.

1797
02:06:11,201 --> 02:06:13,327
Ellis Boyd Redding.

1798
02:06:13,411 --> 02:06:16,789
Your files say you've served
40 years of a life sentence.

1799
02:06:16,873 --> 02:06:19,250
Do you feel you've been rehabilitated?

1800
02:06:21,378 --> 02:06:23,462
Rehabilitated?

1801
02:06:25,006 --> 02:06:27,091
Well, now, let me see.

1802
02:06:28,135 --> 02:06:30,469
You know, I don't have any idea
what that means.

1803
02:06:32,264 --> 02:06:34,807
Well, it means you're ready to rejoin society...

1804
02:06:34,891 --> 02:06:37,434
I know what you think it means, sonny.

1805
02:06:39,813 --> 02:06:41,897
To me, it's just a made-up word.

1806
02:06:42,941 --> 02:06:45,192
A politician's word so that...

1807
02:06:45,277 --> 02:06:50,781
young fellas like yourself
can wear a suit and a tie and have a job.

1808
02:06:53,201 --> 02:06:55,286
What do you really want to know?

1809
02:06:56,454 --> 02:06:58,372
Am I sorry for what I did?

1810
02:06:58,456 --> 02:07:00,166
Well, are you?

1811
02:07:01,793 --> 02:07:04,378
There's not a day goes by I don't feel regret.

1812
02:07:05,964 --> 02:07:09,091
Not because I'm in here
or because you think I should.

1813
02:07:12,888 --> 02:07:14,972
I look back on the way I was then.

1814
02:07:17,559 --> 02:07:19,602
A young...

1815
02:07:19,686 --> 02:07:22,771
stupid kid who committed that terrible crime.

1816
02:07:26,610 --> 02:07:28,694
I wanna talk to him.

1817
02:07:30,071 --> 02:07:32,239
I wanna try and talk some sense to him,

1818
02:07:33,283 --> 02:07:35,367
tell him the way things are.

1819
02:07:37,537 --> 02:07:39,622
But I can't.

1820
02:07:40,832 --> 02:07:42,917
That kid's long gone.

1821
02:07:44,211 --> 02:07:46,295
This old man is all that's left.

1822
02:07:48,423 --> 02:07:49,924
I gotta live with that.

1823
02:07:51,259 --> 02:07:53,052
Rehabilitated?

1824
02:07:53,136 --> 02:07:55,137
It's just a bullshit word.

1825
02:07:55,222 --> 02:08:01,143
So you go on and stamp your form, sonny,
and stop wasting my time.

1826
02:08:02,229 --> 02:08:04,271
Because to tell you the truth,

1827
02:08:04,356 --> 02:08:06,857
I don't give a shit.

1828
02:08:44,980 --> 02:08:47,064
<font color="#ff00ff">(Gate closes)</font>

1829
02:09:06,459 --> 02:09:08,544
<font color="#ff00ff">(Siren passes outside)</font>

1830
02:09:33,069 --> 02:09:35,154
Here you go, miss.

1831
02:09:37,157 --> 02:09:38,615
Rest room break, boss?

1832
02:09:44,664 --> 02:09:48,959
You don't need to ask me every time you need
to go take a piss. Just go. Understand?

1833
02:09:50,170 --> 02:09:51,837
Yes, sir.

1834
02:10:01,890 --> 02:10:04,933
<i><font color="#808080">RED :</font> 40 years
I've been asking permission to piss.</i>

1835
02:10:05,935 --> 02:10:08,145
<i>I can't squeeze a drop without say-so.</i>

1836
02:10:12,275 --> 02:10:14,360
<i>There's a harsh truth to face.</i>

1837
02:10:16,321 --> 02:10:18,655
<i>No way I'm gonna make it on the outside.</i>

1838
02:10:26,873 --> 02:10:30,334
<i>All I do any more
is think of ways to break my parole...</i>

1839
02:10:31,378 --> 02:10:33,462
<i>..so maybe they'd send me back.</i>

1840
02:10:38,968 --> 02:10:41,053
<i>A terrible thing to live in fear.</i>

1841
02:10:42,430 --> 02:10:45,808
<i>Brooks Hatlen knew it, knew it all too well.</i>

1842
02:10:47,977 --> 02:10:50,771
<i>All I want is to be back
where things make sense,</i>

1843
02:10:51,815 --> 02:10:54,316
<i>where I won't have to be afraid all the time.</i>

1844
02:10:57,195 --> 02:10:59,279
<i>Only one thing stops me.</i>

1845
02:11:00,323 --> 02:11:02,408
<i>A promise I made to Andy.</i>

1846
02:11:23,138 --> 02:11:25,222
Here it is.

1847
02:11:35,024 --> 02:11:37,109
Much obliged, sir.

1848
02:15:00,355 --> 02:15:02,439
<font color="#ff00ff">(Bird calls)</font>

1849
02:15:15,912 --> 02:15:17,204
<i>ANDY : Dear Red,</i>

1850
02:15:17,288 --> 02:15:19,748
<i>if you're reading this, you've gotten out.</i>

1851
02:15:19,832 --> 02:15:24,086
<i>And if you've come this far,
maybe you're willing to come a little further.</i>

1852
02:15:24,170 --> 02:15:26,755
<i>You remember the name of the town, don't you?</i>

1853
02:15:29,050 --> 02:15:31,134
Zihuatanejo.

1854
02:15:32,178 --> 02:15:33,387
<i>I could use a good man</i>

1855
02:15:33,471 --> 02:15:35,514
<i>to help me get my project on wheels.</i>

1856
02:15:35,598 --> 02:15:37,724
<i>I'll keep an eye out for you</i>

1857
02:15:37,809 --> 02:15:39,851
<i>and the chessboard ready.</i>

1858
02:15:40,895 --> 02:15:42,270
<i>Remember, Red,</i>

1859
02:15:42,355 --> 02:15:44,398
<i>hope is a good thing.</i>

1860
02:15:44,482 --> 02:15:46,525
<i>Maybe the best of things.</i>

1861
02:15:46,609 --> 02:15:48,694
<i>And no good thing ever dies.</i>

1862
02:15:49,737 --> 02:15:52,197
<i>I will be hoping that this letter finds you</i>

1863
02:15:52,281 --> 02:15:54,324
<i>and finds you well.</i>

1864
02:15:54,409 --> 02:15:56,910
<i>Your friend, Andy.</i>

1865
02:16:30,487 --> 02:16:34,365
<i><font color="#808080">RED :</font> Get busy living or get busy dying.</i>

1866
02:16:36,869 --> 02:16:38,953
<i>That's goddamn right.</i>

1867
02:16:44,460 --> 02:16:46,586
<i>For the second time in my life,</i>

1868
02:16:46,670 --> 02:16:48,755
<i>I'm guilty of committing a crime.</i>

1869
02:16:50,424 --> 02:16:52,508
<i>Parole violation.</i>

1870
02:16:52,509 --> 02:16:56,220
<i>Of course, I doubt they'll toss up
any roadblocks for that.</i>

1871
02:16:57,473 --> 02:16:59,515
<i>Not for an old crook like me.</i>

1872
02:16:59,600 --> 02:17:01,684
Fort Hancock, Texas, please.

1873
02:17:05,397 --> 02:17:09,525
<i>I find I'm so excited I can barely sit still
or hold a thought in my head.</i>

1874
02:17:10,569 --> 02:17:13,571
<i>I think it's the excitement
only a free man can feel.</i>

1875
02:17:13,655 --> 02:17:16,365
<i>A free man at the start of a long journey</i>

1876
02:17:16,450 --> 02:17:19,368
<i>whose conclusion is uncertain.</i>

1877
02:17:22,247 --> 02:17:24,415
<i>I hope I can make it across the border.</i>

1878
02:17:26,293 --> 02:17:29,086
<i>I hope to see my friend and shake his hand.</i>

1879
02:17:31,465 --> 02:17:34,675
<i>I hope the Pacific is as blue
as it has been in my dreams.</i>

1880
02:17:37,429 --> 02:17:39,305
<i>I hope.</i>

